<div class="bar">
  <h1 class="brand">Rubbury &times; Physics</h1>
  <p class="tagline">Measuring the speed of light with a microwave oven and a bar of chocolate.</p>

  <p>
    A microwave oven cavity supports a standing electromagnetic wave at 2.45 GHz. Melt a flat
    sheet of chocolate on the (turntable-removed) cavity floor and it melts fastest at the
    wave's antinodes &mdash; fixed hot spots spaced half a wavelength apart. Measure that
    spacing, and the rest is one equation:
  </p>

  <p class="tagline" style="font-size: 1.3rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;"><code>c = f &times; &lambda;</code></p>

  <p>
    <code>f</code> is the magnetron's frequency, printed on the oven's rating plate (almost
    always 2450 MHz). <code>&lambda;</code> is the wavelength &mdash; double the measured
    spot-to-spot spacing, since adjacent hot spots are &lambda;/2 apart.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use the tabs above to see <strong>why</strong> those hot spots form (Standing Waves),
    look at <strong>photos</strong> from a real run of this experiment (Gallery), or plug in
    your own measurements to get <strong>c</strong> (Calculator).
  </p>
</div>
